	<text>
		<body>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName><add>&#63;</add> Bay</placeName> <date>21<hi rend="sup">st</hi> April 1857</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee>. &#38;c.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Rev Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">I hope you will pardon the liberty I take in this<lb/> trespassing upon your valuable time and attention to claim regard<lb/> for the affairs of an individual who has not the honor to be known<lb/> to you.  Your prominent position among our Brethren in <placeName>America</placeName>&#44; &#38;<lb/> your reputed zeal in Jewish affairs generally have emboldened me<lb/> to address you &#38; made me confident that you will forgive my pardon<lb/> in consideration of the nature of my communication.</p>
				<p>I have had the honor to preside over the congregation Beth Ya<add>&#63;</add> of<lb/> this place for several years &#38; during that time of ministry&#44; it has been<lb/> my good fortune to possess the respect &#38; esteem of all classes of my constituents.<lb/>  Unhappily&#44; the depression of affairs in the <placeName>island</placeName> generally&#44; has extend<lb/>&#45;ed its influence into our holy institution &#38; its diminished resources have<lb/> forced the rulers to retrench its expenditure commensurately with the times.<lb/>  I have thus with an increasing family been subjected to a diminution<lb/> of a stipend never more than adequate to a respectable living.  Unfortu&#45;<lb/>&#45;nately this is too limited a sphere &#38; furnishes no opportunity to improve<lb/> my circumstances by any employment reconcilable with the dis&#45;<lb/>&#45;tinguished profession&#44; of which I am an humble member.  The<lb/> Jewish children of the community do not amount to six&#8212;all<lb/> attempts at book making &#38; class teaching &#38;c have proved <add>&#63;</add></p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>&#38; then it is that although I otherwise enjoy an enviable lot in the<lb/> possession of a prize in the usually poor lottery of Jewish ministry&#44;<lb/> I am forced to sacrifice it&#44; for the welfare of my family.</p>
				<p>In my search after some advantageous change&#44; I direct myself to<lb/> you&#44; with<add>&#63;</add> the promises that my desires are limited within the boundaries<lb/> of a respectable living&#44; I respectfully solicit any information you may<lb/> possess concerning those congregations in <placeName>America</placeName> who may be in need of<lb/> ministers.  If to this&#44; you will be good enough to add a few words of<lb/> counsel&#44; the favor will be considerably enhanced.  It might be<lb/> as well to state that I have received what is termed a liberal<lb/> education&#8212;am accustomed frequently to disperse instruction from<lb/> the pulpit &#38; possess professional credentials from the <persName>Revd Dr Meldola</persName><lb/> Hazan <persName>De Sola</persName> &#38;c &#38;c.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">In conclusion&#44; I beg to refer you to the <persName>Revd M N Nathan</persName><lb/> of <placeName>New Orleans</placeName> &#38; the <persName>Revd Abm DeSola</persName> of <placeName>Montreal</placeName>&#44; who will as&#45;<lb/>suredly vouch for my <hi rend="underline">principle</hi> &#38; convince you that your good<lb/>&#45;ness will not be un<add>&#63;</add> <add>&#63;</add> up.</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">Your very obliged servant</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)"><persName role="author">A P Mendes</persName></p>
				<p>PS.</p>
				<p>The congregation of <placeName>Richmond Va</placeName></p>
				<p>has been especially pointed out to me.</p>
				<p>May I solicit your advice&#63;</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)"><persName role="author">APM.</persName></p>
			<pb n="3"/>
			<p rend="indent(2)"><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
